{"title_page": "Repton School", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{For|the school of the same name in Dubai|Repton School Dubai}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Repton School\n | logo                    = Reptoncrest.png\n | image                   = ReptonSchool2007.JPG\n | alt                     = \n | caption                 = \n | motto                   = {{Lang-la|Porta Vacat Culpa}}\n | motto_translation       = The gate is free from blame\n | address                 = [[Repton]]\n | city                    = \n | county                  = [[Derbyshire]]\n | postcode                = DE65 6FH\n | country                 = England\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|52.8409|-1.5510|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n | other_name              = <!-- or | other_names = -->\n | former_name             = <!-- or | former_names = -->\n | type                    = [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|Independent]], [[Day school|day]] and boarding school\n | religious_affiliation   = Christian\n | established             = {{Unbulleted list|''Bequest made:'' {{Start date|df=y|1557}}|''Land acquired:'' 1559}}\n | founder                 = [[John Port (died 1557)|Sir John Port]]\n | closed                  = \n | local_authority         = [[Derbyshire County Council]]\n | trust                   = \n | urn                     = 113009\n | ofsted                  = \n | headmaster              = Mark Semmence<ref>/https://www.repton.org.uk/about-repton/welcome-from-the-head</ref>\n | staff                   = \n | gender                  = [[Mixed-sex education|Mixed]]\n | age_range               = 13\u201318\n | enrolment               = 635 (2020)<ref name=\"GOV.UK\">{{cite web |title=Repton School |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Establishments/Establishment/Details/113009 |website=Get information about schools |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom |accessdate=26 March 2019 }}</ref>\n | capacity                = 680<ref name=\"GOV.UK\" />\n | campus_size             = \n | campus_type             = \n | houses                  = [[#Houses and pastoral arrangements|10]]\n | colours                 = Navy and yellow\n | accreditation           = <!-- or | accreditations = -->\n | publication             = \n | yearbook                = \n | affiliation             = <!-- or | affiliations = -->\n | alumni                  = [[#Old Reptonians|Old Reptonians]]\n | free_label              = Preparatory school\n | free_text               = [[Repton Preparatory School]]\n | website                 = {{URL|repton.org.uk}}\n | footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Repton School''' is a [[Mixed-sex education|mixed]] co-educational [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] school, for pupils from ages 13 to 18, in [[Repton]], [[Derbyshire]], England, United Kingdom. The school was [[Single-sex education|boys only]] until girls were admitted to the [[sixth form]] early in the 1970s, and by the 1990s it was fully [[Mixed-sex education|co-educational]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Mike|title=Exploring the village of Repton \u2013 one of South Derbyshire's gems|url=http://www.derbyshirelife.co.uk/out-about/places/exploring_the_village_of_repton_one_of_south_derbyshire_s_gems_1_4225773|website=Derbyshire Life|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:JohnPortKright.jpg|left|thumb|Brass of Sir John Port on his tomb in St Helen's parish church, [[Etwall]], Derbyshire. He founded Repton School.]]\n\n===Origins===\nThe school was founded by a 1557 legacy in the will of Sir [[John Port (died 1557)|John Port]] of [[Etwall]], leaving funds for a grammar school at [[Etwall]] or Repton, condition on the students praying daily for the souls of his family.<ref name=\"JP\">{{cite ODNB|title=John Port|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/22552|accessdate=11 June 2013|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/22552|year=2004}}</ref>\n\nBuildings at the site of Repton Priory were granted for the school in 1559 by Gilbert Thacker. Not long after this, lawsuits began between the school and the Thacker family. These focused on access issues, <ref name=\"Records\">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/recordsandremin00messgoog/recordsandremin00messgoog_djvu.txt|title=Records and Reminiscences of Repton|website=archive.org|accessdate=31 May 2016}}</ref> and relations with the Thackers deteriorated to the extent that that, by the 1650s, the school and the family were embroiled in litigation:  the school commenced an action against the Thacker family in 1642; the family also brought an action against the school which was settled out of court. The atmosphere around the conflict was sufficiently aggressive that the Thackers diverted drains into the school's buildings by constructing dams, and in 1670, a wall was built to keep the parties apart.<ref name=\"Records\" />\n\nA pupil's letter home in 1728 relates to his father that the headmaster, George Fletcher, would withhold meals from the boys if they were unable to recite scripture.<ref name=\"Records\" /> \n\nPupil numbers swung between 80 and 200 in the first hundred years, but as the school was free until 1768 it is unclear how teaching was afforded. \n\nThe headmaster kept cattle in a room within the school around this period.<ref name=\"Records\" />\n\n=== Decline ===\n\nThe school's reputation and operation declined in the 1700s and the 1800s, and pupil numbers were under 50 by 1833, with a former pupil recalled after leaving:<blockquote>\n\"even more than the paucity of its numbers, was the almost total absence of all those facilities... cricket ground we had none. Football was played upon the gravel, between the Arch, and the broken pillars...No gymnasium, no fives court, no racquet court...No French, no German, no Music, no Natural Science... No chapel, no master's house beyond the Arch, no bridge (at first) across the Trent, no railway.... Why did even 50 boys resort to Sir John Port's old School?\"<ref name=Records/>\n</blockquote>\nAlthough by the 1830s some of the changes of reforming schoolmaster of [[Rugby School|Rugby Schoo]]<nowiki/>l Dr. [[Thomas Arnold]] were being implemented at the school,<ref name=Records/> the school declined further in the following decades.[[File:Repton Grammar School, Repton, Derbyshire; gateway. Tinted l Wellcome V0014398.jpg|alt=Repton Grammar School, Repton, Derbyshire: gateway. Tinted lithograph by Hullmandel & Walton|thumb|Repton Grammar School gateway: tinted [[lithograph]] by [[Charles Joseph Hullmandel|Hullmandel & Walton]]|left]]The decline was stopped by headmaster Steuart Pears, who worked hard to raise the school's status and reputation.{{cn|date=February 2020}} A major effort was made, with the [[Charity Commission for England and Wales|Charity Commissioners]] and the [[Clarendon Commission]], to have the school accepted as one of the great public schools.<ref name=\"Records\" /> Repton was excluded from their 1864 report, however, which included only nine schools, and the school was thus excluded from the [[Public Schools Act 1868]] and hence the status of being a [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public school]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.educationengland.org.uk/documents/acts/1868-public-schools-act.html|title=Text of the Public Schools Act, 1868|date=17 February 2013|website=Education in England|publisher=Derek Gillard|access-date=31 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the early centuries of the school's development, a pupil-conferred role called \"Cock of the School\" was accepted within the pupil body, a boy would be identified as the holder of this office after fighting between likely candidates. \n\nOnce a boy was incumbent in this role, the younger boys were regarded as his slaves and customarily required to defer to him and to do his work; writing in 1907, G. S. Messiter described the practice as an \"ancient custom\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=George Stephen Messiter|url=https://archive.org/details/recordsandremin00messgoog|title=Records and Reminiscences of Repton|date=1907|publisher=A.J. Lawrence|others=Harvard University|page=[https://archive.org/details/recordsandremin00messgoog/page/n52 41]}}</ref>\n\n===Recovery===\n[[File:Repton School Chapel - geograph.org.uk - 273610.jpg|thumb|Repton School Chapel|alt=]]\nIn 1884 a chapel was added to the school's buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-82781-the-chapel-repton-school-repton-derbyshir|title=The Chapel, Repton School, Repton, Derbyshire|website=British Listed Buildings|access-date=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nA number of headmasters of Repton went on to senior Church of England positions in the twentieth century. Dr. Furneaux was headmaster from 1882 to 1900, and, after retiring from Repton, he became [[Dean of Winchester]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.winchester-cathedral.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/Safe-Sound-and-Secure.pdf|title=Winchester Cathedral: Safe, Sound, and Secure: A Centenary Tribute to William Walker the Diver |last=Farthing |first=David |website=Winchester Cathedral |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Lionel Ford]] was headmaster from 1901\u20131910, and he went on to be [[Dean of York]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1349397/Neville-Ford.html|title=Neville Ford|journal=Daily Telegraph|date=2000-07-19|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>  [[Hubert Burge]] was headmaster between 1900 and 1901, after leaving the school he would become [[Bishop of Oxford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxford.anglican.org/who-we-are/history-of-the-diocese/bishops-of-oxford/|title=List of Bishops of Oxford since 1542|website=Diocese of Oxford|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[William Temple (bishop)|William Temple]] was headmaster for four years from 1910 to 1914, and he went on to become [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] in 1942.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spartacus-educational.com/REtempleW.htm|title=William Temple|website=Spartacus Educational|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nRecent research published in ''Picturing the closet: male secrecy and homosexual visibility in Britain,'' by Dominic Janes, found that between 1900 and 1914, the \"Black Book\" (the school discipline record) recorded 38 instances of immorality within the pupil community; punishments for this activity ranged from caning to expulsion,<ref name=\"DJ\">{{Cite book|title=Picturing the closet : male secrecy and homosexual visibility in Britain|last=Dominic.|first=Janes|isbn=9780190205638|location=New York|oclc=884665212|year = 2015}}</ref> most of the activity was performed in groups, with Janes concluding \"what we are seeing here is [not] the victimisation of couples, but the periodic purges of small cadres of peers\".<ref name=\"DJ\" /> Immediately after this period, when [[Geoffrey Fisher]] became headmaster in 1914, an account was as follows: \"homosexuality was rife. Fisher immediately expelled two senior boys and began to rule with a very firm hand\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=The bishops|last=Trevor.|first=Beeson|date=2002|publisher=SCM Press|isbn=9780334029168|location=London|oclc=59450207}}</ref>  Fisher would go on to become [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], but his tenure as headmaster has been linked to \"blithe.. extraordinary violence and psychological cruelty\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Renton|first=Alex|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/apr/08/school-boarding-secrets-crimes-alex-renton-kipling-rowling-dahl-churchill|title=School of hard knocks: the dark underside to boarding school books|date=2017-04-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[File:Harold Abrahams 1924.jpg|alt=Harold Abrahams, joined the school in 1914|thumb|[[Harold Abrahams]], pictured here at the 1924 Olympics, joined the school in 1914]][[Harold Abrahams]] CBE, the Olympic champion in the 100m sprint in the 1924 Paris Olympics, depicted in the 1981 film ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'', joined the school in 1914. Recalling his time at the school, Abrahams said he encountered [[antisemitism]], often feeling [[Bullying|bullied]] and alone.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PCpTBgAAQBAJ|title=Sneaker Century: A History of Athletic Shoes|last=Keyser|first=Amber J.|date=1 January 2015|publisher=Twenty-First Century Books|isbn=9781467763097}}</ref>\n\nIn 1907 a gymnasium was added. This building is now grade II listed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-82782-gymnasium-and-attached-gates-repton-schoo|title=Gymnasium and Attached Gates, Repton School, Repton, Derbyshire|first=Good|last=Stuff|website=British Listed Buildings |accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> In this decade the chapel was enlarged, and the Science Block, the Gymnasium, Armoury, Shooting Range and Swimming Bath were built, and the Priory \u2018Tithe\u2019 Barn turned into the Art School.<ref>{{Cite book|last=The Central Education Co. Ltd|title=Repton School, an introductory booklet|publisher=The Central Education Co. Ltd|year=1959|isbn=|location=Derby|pages=51}}</ref>\n\nA reforming master, [[Victor Gollancz]], established evening class in political education for the boys in the early 1900s. The school considered that this tended to \"undermine the authority of the teachers by encouraging the pupils to ask questions and work with the boys in a colaborative<!--sic?--> way\", so he was termed a \"traitor\" and a \"pacifist\" and was dismissed form the school.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=E6uoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT302&lpg=PT302&dq=repton+school+corporal+punishment#v=onepage&q=repton%20school&f=false|title=Public School Literature, Civic Education and the Politics of Male Adolescence|last=Holt|first=Jenny|date=2016 |publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351907668}}</ref>\n\n1,912 former pupils of the school served in the [[First World War]], of whom 355 died in service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.repton.org.uk/great-war-exhibition|title=Great War Exhibition|website=repton.org.uk|access-date=2 July 2016}}</ref> A war memorial was added to the school's site in 1921.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-82776-war-memorial-at-repton-school-repton-derb|title=War Memorial at Repton School \u2013 Repton \u2013 Derbyshire \u2013 England |website=British Listed Buildings|last=Stuff|first=Good |accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1917 the writers [[Christopher Isherwood]] and [[Edward Upward]] began their time at Repton. They formed a friendship which continued when they both at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]. They revolted at school against everything associated with the establishment, which they called \"the other side\", and Upward reflected after leaving that \"everyone was homosexual, up to a point, at Repton\". <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/4192502/Hello-to-Berlin-boys-and-books.html|title=Hello to Berlin, boys and books|journal=The Daily Telegraph|date=27 May 2004|accessdate=5 August 2018|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> In the 1920s, the poet [[Vernon Watkins]] was sent to Repton. His gentle character provoked regular bullying in his early years. When he died, the school claimed him as \"perhaps the best poet Repton has had\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/templates/article.jsp?articleid=58903&back=|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, \"Vernon Watkins\" entry|last=Watkins|first=Meic|year=2004|website=Oxford DNB|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=31 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe writer and painter [[Denton Welch]] was a pupil in the 1930s, and his account of running away from the school, subsequent return and miserable final term there is first part of his autobiographical novel ''[[Maiden Voyage (novel)|Maiden Voyage]]'' (1943).\n\nIn 1924 George Gilbert Stocks, a director of music at the school, set it to the hymn ''Dear Lord and Father of Mankind'' to the tune ''Repton'' for use in the school's chapel.  He took the melody from [[Hubert Parry]]'s  1888 contralto aria \"Long since in Egypt's plenteous land\" in his oratorio ''Judith''. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://timelyscores.com/2017/07/20/repton-rest-hymn-tunes/|title=Dear Lord and Father of Mankind|date=20 July 2017|accessdate=13 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014034317/https://timelyscores.com/2017/07/20/repton-rest-hymn-tunes/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Roald Dahl (1982).jpg|alt=Roald Dahl gives accounts of his time at Repton in his book 'Boy'|thumb|150px|[[Roald Dahl]] gives accounts of his time at Repton in his autobiography]]\n\nThe writer [[Roald Dahl]] attended in the 1930s. His experiences are related in his semi-autobiographical book ''[[Boy (book)|Boy]]'', in which he describes an environment of ritual cruelty, [[fagging]] and [[School corporal punishment|beatings]], later stating \"I was appalled by the fact that masters and senior boys were allowed literally to wound other boys, and sometimes quite severely... I couldn't get over it. I never have got over it.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Briggs|first=Julia|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GCWoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT410&lpg=PT410&dq=I+was+appalled+by+the+fact+that+masters+and+senior+boys+were+allowed+literally+to+wound+other+boys,+and+sometimes+quite+severely...+I+couldn't+get+over+it.+I+never+have+got+over+it#v=onepage|title=Popular Children's Literature in Britain|last2=Butts|first2=Dennis|date=2016-12-05|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-351-91003-3|language=en}}</ref> An account of a beating of boy called Micheal, in [[Roald Dahl|Roald Dahl's]] 1984 autobiographical book ''[[Boy (book)|Boy]]'',{{NoteTag|\"... he was ordered to take down his trousers and kneel on the headmaster\u2019s sofa with the top half of his body hanging over one end of the sofa. The great man then gave him one terrific crack. After that there was a pause. The cane was put down and the headmaster began filling his pipe from a tin of tobacco. He also started to lecture the kneeling boy about sin and wrongdoing. Soon, the cane was picked up again and a second tremendous crack was administered upon the trembling buttocks. Then the pipe-filling business and the lecture went on for maybe 30 seconds. Then came the third crack of the cane ... At the end of it all, a basin, a sponge and a small clean towel were produced by the headmaster, and the victim was told to wash away the blood before pulling up his trousers.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Roald |last=Dahl |authorlink=Roald Dahl |title=Boy |title-link=Boy (book) |year=1984 |publisher=[[Jonathan Cape|Cape]]}}</ref>}} was attributed by Dahl to Fisher. But Dahl's biographer, [[Jeremy Treglown]], has pointed out he was mistaken: the beating was in May 1933, a year after Fisher had left Repton, and headmaster concerned was [[John Christie (headmaster)|John Christie]], Fisher's successor.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Treglown|first1=Jeremy|authorlink1=Jeremy Treglown|title=Roald Dahl: a Biography|location=London | publisher=Faber & Faber|year=1994 |isbn=978-0-571-16573-5 |page=21}}</ref>\n\n=== Second World War and after ===\nThe headmaster from 1937 to 1943 was [[Michael Clarke (priest)|H.G. Michael Clarke]], he left the school to pursue an eclisiastical career and became [[Dean of Birmingham Cathedral|Provost of Birmingham Cathedral]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F39304|title=The Discovery Service|last=Archives|first=The National|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> He led the school during one of the most difficult periods of its history, when mounting debts and falling numbers, together with the effects of the war, led to questions as to the continuing viability of the institution; Clarke was obliged to close departments and two houses (The Cross and Latham).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hillman|first=Nicholas|authorlink=Nick Hillman|date=1 December 2010|title=The Public Schools Commission: 'Impractical, Expensive and Harmful to Children'?|journal=Contemporary British History|volume=24|issue=4|pages=511\u2013531|doi=10.1080/13619462.2010.518413|issn=1361-9462}}</ref> The school owed \u00a350,000 (around \u00a33.5 million at today's prices) and, in 1941, the [[Ministry of Education (United Kingdom)|Board of Education]] said its \"future is doubtful\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hillman|first=Nicholas|authorlink=Nick Hillman|date=1 December 2010|title=The Public Schools Commission: 'Impractical, Expensive and Harmful to Children'?|journal=Contemporary British History|volume=24|issue=4|pages=511\u2013531|doi=10.1080/13619462.2010.518413|issn=1361-9462}}</ref> \n\nThe total number of pupils was 353 at the outbreak of war, which fell to 273 in 1943. Numbers recovered in the late 1940s, and The Cross was able to reopen in 1945 and Latham House in 1947. By 1957, the school was in better health, and was full with 470 pupils.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hillman|first=Nick|authorlink=Nick Hillman|year=2012|title=Repton and the HMC during the Second World War |url=http://www.johncatt.com/downloads/pdf/magazines/ccr/ccr49_1/ccr49_1.pdf|journal=Conference & Common Room|volume=49|issue=1|access-date=19 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the Second World War, 188 former members of the school died serving in the armed forces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ww1-yorkshires.org.uk/html-files/repton-school.htm|title=The Yorkshire Regiment, Local War Memorials|website=ww1-yorkshires.org.uk|accessdate=3 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n1957 saw the 400 year centenary of the school, celebrated with a Royal visit from The Queen and Duke of Edinburgh.  A new Chemistry Block and new workshops within the Precinct, as well as extensive alterations to the Science Block.  John Gammell took office as headmaster in 1968 and during his tenure girls began to be educated at Repton. It started with the arrival of two girls in 1970. By 1979 the first purpose-built girls\u2019 boarding house was opened.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Plowright|first=John|title=Repton to the end|publisher=Third Millennium Publishin|year=2007|isbn=166382208|location=London|pages=28}}</ref>\n[[File:Jeremy Clarkson 2008.jpg|thumb|Jeremy Clarkson attended Repton in the 1970s. ]]\nFagging is recorded as having taken place at Repton into the late 20th century.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Roach|first=Martin|title=The Top Gear Story \u2013 The 100% Unofficial Story of the Most Famous Car Show... In The World|publisher=John Blake Publishing|year=2014|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref> Jeremy Clarkson noted after leaving that, \"I suffered many terrible things. I was thrown on an hourly basis into the ice plunge pool, dragged from my bed in the middle of the night and beaten, made to lick the lavatories clean and all the usual humiliations that... turn a small boy into a gibbering, sobbing, suicidal wreck... they glued my records together, snapped my compass, ate my biscuits, defecated in my tuck box and they cut my trousers in half\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/celebrity/clarkson-was-suicidal-at-school-after-being-bullied/ar-AAbWf5j|title=Clarkson was suicidal at school after being bullied|date=2016-06-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605073627/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/celebrity/clarkson-was-suicidal-at-school-after-being-bullied/ar-AAbWf5j|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-date=5 June 2016}}</ref>  In the 1980s. [[Chris Adams (cricketer)|Chris Adams]] was at the school and subsequently observed, \"The ingrained hierarchy whereby the older boys would subject the younger pupils to a lot of misery through the system of fagging. It was basically a system of slavery and I hated seeing the young lads literally trembling with fear\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Chris|first=Adams|title=Grizzly : my life and times in cricket|date=2015-10-14|isbn=9781785311239|location=Durrington|oclc=949931533}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1980s, the old [[Sanatorium]] was converted into a Music School.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Plowright|first=John|title=Repton to the End.|publisher=Third Millennium|year=2007|isbn=166382208|location=London|pages=41}}</ref>  Another fall in numbers in the 1990s required Graham Jones, headmaster from 1987 to 2003, to close two boys boarding houses -- Brook House and The Hall -- taking their occupants and forming a new house, School House.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Plowright|first=John|title=Repton to the end|date=2007|isbn=978-1-903942-55-0|language=English|oclc=166382208}}</ref>\n\n=== 21st century ===\n[[File:Repton School Business Centre and Gallery. - geograph.org.uk - 898867.jpg|thumb|Repton School Business Centre and Gallary, in a former shop]]\nThe school marked its 450th anniversary in 2007 with a royal visit from [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|HRH Prince Edward]].  Celebrations also included concerts featuring [[Michael Ball]] and [[Bryan Ferry]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Plowright|first=John|title=Repton to the end|publisher=Third Millennium Publishing|year=2007|isbn=166382208|location=London|pages=165}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 the 1957 400 Hall theatre was remodelled, by [[Avery Associates Architects]],<ref>{{cite web |title=400 Hall Theatre AJ Buildings Library |url=https://www.ajbuildingslibrary.co.uk/projects/display/id/6917 |website=www.ajbuildingslibrary.co.uk |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref> following a \u00a33.3 million upgrade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-15753674|title=Repton School theatre reopens after \u00a33.3m revamp|date=16 November 2011|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 August 2017}}</ref> In 2013 a \u00a39&nbsp;million science block was built. During the preparations for the building work, archaeological digs were undertaken which indicated the site had been occupied in the [[Roman Britain|Roman period]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repton.org.uk/Royal-Opening-for-Reptons-Science-Priory|title=Royal Opening for Repton's Science Priory|website=|publisher=Repton|accessdate=13 October 2017}}<br>- {{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Discovery-Roman-past-real-life-school-history/story-16902012-detail/story.html|title=Discovery of Roman past is a real-life school history lesson|date=14 September 2012|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=8 June 2016}} {{Dead link|date=August 2018|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>  Around this time, the old [[Squash (sport)|Squash Courts]] were made into a new gallery and textiles studio for the Art department.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Plowright|first=John|title=Repton to the End|publisher=Third Millennium|year=2007|isbn=166382208|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe period 2015-2019 saw some rapid cycling of leadership of the school. Nevertheless, a new teaching block, the Lynam Thomas Building, in the Precinct and a major refurbishment programme being undertaken.  In November 2019 [[Adam Peaty]] opened a newly redeveloped \u00a36m sports centre at the school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/news/2019-11-21/Repton-School-Sports-Centre-opened-by-Olympian-Adam-Peaty-MBE|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> Alastair Land was headmaster from 2016 to 2019, leaving to become headmaster at [[Harrow School|Harrow]], and was succeeded as Headmaster by Mark Semmence.\n\nIn November 2019, [[Libby Lane|Revd Libby Lane]], [[Bishop of Derby|Lord Bishop of Derby]] (the first female bishop in the Church of England) was appointed Visitor of Repton School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/news/2019-11-04/Bishop-of-Derby-appointed-Visitor-of-Repton-School|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2020 it was announced that the school would be merging with [[Foremarke Hall]] School from September 2020.<ref name=\"derbytelegraph\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/burton/two-derbyshire-schools-merge-3758103|title=These two Derbyshire schools are to merge|date=2020-01-20|work=derbytelegraph|access-date=2020-01-24|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Shortly after, St Wystan's School announced it was exploratory talks to join Repton.<ref name=\"derbytelegraph\" />\n\n== Fees and inspection ==\nIn 2019/20, fees were \u00a336,783 for boarders and \u00a327,207 for day pupils per year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/admissions/fees|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nThere are scholarships available for drama, sport, art, music, academic capacity and \"all-rounder talent\"; these do not exceed 20% of the school's fees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/admissions/scholarships-bursaries|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>  There is also some bursary assistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repton.org.uk/scholarships-bursaries|title=Scholarships & Bursaries |website= |publisher=Repton School |accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe school is inspected by the [[Independent Schools Inspectorate]]. An integrated inspection took place in March 2014, finding the school to be \"exceptionally successful in achieving its aims... the quality of the pupils' achievements is excellent\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isi.net/school/repton-school-6835|title=March 2014 ISI Inspection|website= |publisher=ISI}}</ref>\n\nAn emergency inspection in January 2015 was ordered by the [[Department for Education]] reviewing welfare and safeguarding compliance under the Independent School Standard Regulations (ISSRs) and the National Minimum Standards for Boarding (NMSB). The school failed to meet these national minimum standards at that inspection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://isischools.devprocess.com/DownloadReport.aspx?t=c&r=FLWEV6835_20150121.pdf&s=6835|title=Emergency Inspection 2015|last=Independent Schools Inspectorate|website=|publisher=Independent Schools Inspectorate|access-date=5 August 2015}}</ref> \n\nA regulatory Compliance Inspection took place in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isi.net/school/repton-school-6835?results=true|title=Repton School :: Independent Schools Inspectorate|website=www.isi.net|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> \n\n== Houses and pastoral arrangements ==\nA little over two-thirds of pupils are boarders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukboardingschools.com/schools/repton-school/|title=Repton School|date=16 July 2013|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> Former houses that have renamed or redeveloped include: The Hall (at one time divided into A-K and L-Z) \u2013 now known as School House; and Brook House.\n\nThe school currently has 10 houses: six for boys and four for girls:\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* The Abbey (girls)\n* The Cross (boys)\n* Field House (girls)\n* The Garden (girls)\n* Latham House (boys)\n* The Mitre (girls)\n* New House (boys)\n* The Orchard (boys)\n* The Priory (boys)\n* School House (boys)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/boarding-houses/house-life-pastoral-care|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Sports and clubs==\n[[File:Bunny Austin (1936).jpg|thumb|[[Bunny Austin]] attended Repton School. ]]\nThe school competes in various sports,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.repton.org.uk/sport2|title=Repton School Sport|website=repton.org.uk|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> its focus sports are: football (winter), hockey (spring), cricket (summer) for boys; and hockey (winter), netball (spring), tennis (summer) for girls, and swimming through the year for both genders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/sport/focus-sports|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> \n\nNotable sporting former pupils include the 1932 Wimbledon tennis finalist, [[Bunny Austin]], and several first-class cricketers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reptonpilgrims.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=55:repton-school-1st-class-cricketers&catid=37:1st-class-cricketers&Itemid=60|title=Repton Pilgrims Cricket Club|website=Repton Pilgrims Cricket Club|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2013, six former pupils played together in an international hockey match.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/hockey/10478137/Repton-School-claim-hockey-history-as-six-former-pupils-play-in-GB-v-Germany-series.html |title=Repton School claim hockey history as six former pupils play in GB v Germany series |first=Rod |last=Gilmour |date=27 November 2013 |accessdate=13 October 2017 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location= London}}</ref> \n\nThe school has a [[Combined Cadet Force]] and a music school, as well as various after-school clubs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.repton.org.uk/extra-curricular |title=StackPath |access-date=16 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520125118/http://www.repton.org.uk/extra-curricular |archive-date=20 May 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  [[Adam Peaty]], the Olympic swimmer, attended the school for a period on a scholarship after his potential was identified.\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Sexual abuse ===\n\nThe Charity Commission received a number of safeguarding-related serious incident reports from Repton School in February 2018, and it commented \"[i]ncidents of this nature are of serious concern\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/repton-school-allegations-charity-commission-1394332|title=Repton School regulator has 'serious concern' over safeguarding incidents|date=1 April 2018|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=7 April 2018|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Incidents leading to this included:\n\n* A former head of physics, John Mitchell, who was found to have abused a position of trust contrary to s.16(1)(a) of the [[Sexual Offences Act 2003]] on 6 December 2014 when he engaged in sexual activity with a female between the age of 13 and 17 and he did not believe that she was 18 or over. He also communicated in a sexual way and with sexual motivations to this same pupil. He was disqualified from teaching indefinitely by the [[National College for Teaching and Leadership]], following a finding that this was unacceptable professional conduct.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/506803/Web_decision_-_John_Mitchell.pdf|title=Mr John Mitchell: Professional conduct panel outcome|date=2 March 2016|website=|publisher=National College for Teaching and Leadership|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref>\n* In October 2017 a former pupil began proceedings against the school, claiming negligence on the school's part, in connection with an alleged [[rape]] of that pupil by another pupil in 2014, when a 17-year-old pupil was arrested on suspicion of carrying out two rapes at the school;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/teenager-arrested-over-two-rape-allegations-at-jeremy-clarkson-s-old-private-school-9890012.html|title=Teenager arrested over two rape allegations at Jeremy Clarkson's old private school|date=28 November 2017|work=The Independent|accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> in this action it is understood that it was claimed that the school failed to supervise or discipline its pupil. The claimant made a request of the Derbyshire Constabulary for the papers from its investigation, which the police refused to provide without a court order.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boardingconcern.org.uk/2017/10/09/repton-school-sued-failing-protect-pupil-rapist/|title=Repton School sued for failing to protect pupil from a 'rapist'|date=9 October 2017|work=Boarding Concern|accessdate=7 April 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408011010/https://www.boardingconcern.org.uk/2017/10/09/repton-school-sued-failing-protect-pupil-rapist/|archive-date=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n* In 2018 four members of the school's staff were subject to police investigation for inappropriate sexual conduct towards children.  In August 2018, one of these individuals, Jeremy Woodside, a 28-year-old former organist at the school, was placed on the [[Sex offender registry|Sex Offender's Register]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/repton-school-sex-offenders-register-1857939|title=Former Repton School staff member placed on sex offenders' register|date=3 August 2018|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=5 August 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804120309/https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/repton-school-sex-offenders-register-1857939|archive-date=4 August 2018|issn=0307-1235}} </ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/crime/106206341/christchurch-pianist-on-british-sex-offender-register|title=Christchurch pianist on British sex offender register|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> The chronology of those issues emerging in early 2018 was as follows: \n** on 29 January, 2018, police arrested a member of staff on suspicion of attempting [[Child sexual abuse|sexual contact with a child]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/repton-school-arrest-child-sex-1203554|title=Repton School staff member accused of attempting sexual contact with child|date=14 February 2018|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=18 March 2018|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n** on 14 March, 2018, a second police investigation into a staff member, relating to safeguarding concerns, was launched;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Crowson|first=Isaac|url=https://www.burtonmail.co.uk/news/local-news/shock-second-former-repton-school-1310427|title=Another former staff member at Repton School under investigation|date=14 March 2018|work=Burton Mail|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n**on 26 March, 2018 allegations against a further two members of staff were reported.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/repton-school-allegations-against-staff-1376483|title=Repton School: allegations made about two more staff members|date=2018-03-26|work=derbytelegraph|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, a 53-year-old former teacher appeared in court after being charged with a number of sex offences against underage girls, including [[indecent assault]] and [[gross indecency]] with a child. The offences are alleged to have taken place in the 1990s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/trial-date-moved-case-ex-3666586|title=Trial date moved in case of ex-Repton teacher accused of sex offences|date=2019-12-23|work=derbytelegraph|access-date=2020-01-04|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/former-teacher-charged-indecently-assaulting-2744842|title=Former teacher charged with indecently assaulting pupils at school|date=10 April 2019|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=21 April 2019|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He will stand trial for 11 charges in December 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/ex-repton-teacher-pleads-not-2860403|title=Ex-Repton teacher pleads not guilty to indecent assaults on underage girls|date=13 May 2019|newspaper=Derby Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n=== Incidents ===\nIn 2014, Southern Derbyshire Magistrates\u2019 Court fined the school \u00a310,000 following a guilty plea to a health and safety charge after an incident of negligence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cqms-ltd.co.uk/derbyshire-school-fined-after-grandmother-falls-from-stairs/|title=Derbyshire school fined after grandmother falls from stairs|last=QCMS|date=|website=QCMS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In April 2019, a teacher tested positive for drink-driving after police saw his vehicle mount a kerb and then enter the school grounds. He was subsequently convicted and banned from driving for 20 months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/repton-school-teacher-england-hockey-2725962|title=Repton school teacher and England hockey ace caught drink-driving|date=7 April 2019|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=21 April 2019|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Two months later a chemical spillage at the school's sports centre resulted in nine individuals needing precautionary treatment, as a result of a chlorine leak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/nine-treated-following-chemical-spill-3017399|title=Nine treated following chemical spill at top Derbyshire school|website=Derbyshire Telegraph|accessdate=24 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Fee fixing and gender pay gap===\nIn September 2005, the school was one of fifty independent schools operating [[Independent school fee fixing scandal|independent school fee-fixing]], in breach of the [[Competition Act 1998|Competition Act, 1998]]. All of the schools involved were ordered to abandon this practice, pay a nominal penalty of \u00a310,000 each and to make ex-gratia payments totalling three million pounds into a trust designed to benefit pupils who attended the schools during the period in respect of which fee information had been shared.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Halpin |first=Halpin |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/independent-schools-face-huge-fines-over-cartel-to-fix-fees-rcwcznjnvnt |title=Independent schools face huge fines over cartel to fix fees |access-date=2020-02-29 |issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20100402135855tf_/http://www.oft.gov.uk/news/press/2006/182-06|title=Office of Fair Trading Press Release|last=|first=|date=21 December 2006|website=National Ara chive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 Feb 2020}}</ref> The Bursar at the time was Carl Bilson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/_2v6dAdpo4YcFzO_a8bWST3hKgA/appointments|title=Carl Peter BILSON - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House)|website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\nFemale staff members were paid 56-57% less than their male coworkers at the school in 2018,<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://gender-pay-gap.service.gov.uk/Employer/2xIbxNxU/2018|title=Repton School gender pay gap data / 2018-19 - GOV.UK|website=gender-pay-gap.service.gov.uk|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> and 50% less in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gender-pay-gap.service.gov.uk/Employer/2xIbxNxU/2019|title=REPTON SCHOOL gender pay gap data / 2019-20 - GOV.UK|website=gender-pay-gap.service.gov.uk|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n== International schools ==\n[[File:WTemple.jpg|thumb|William Temple was headmaster of Repton, but went on to become Arch Bishop of Canterbury]]\nThe school set up Repton International Schools Ltd (RISL) in 2013 to establish, develop and maintain the highest quality British international schools. The client schools are generally funded by partners, sometimes private equity firms, who are licensed to use the Repton School \"brand\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reptoninternational.com/History-Aims-and-Purpose|title=History, Aims & Purpose |website=|publisher= Repton International Schools Ltd|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> RISL covenants its profits to Repton School Trust in the UK, which helps fund capital projects and bursaries.\n\nClient schools comprise: [[Repton School Dubai]], which opened in September 2007 and is situated on a site in Nad al Sheba;{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} Repton School Abu Dhabi, which opened in 2013 on [[Al Reem Island]], [[Abu Dhabi]]; Foremarke Dubai opened in 2013 and is located in Dubiotech, Al Barsha South and the Repton New English School in [[Amman]], Jordan.\n\nFurther relationships are in development in, amongst other places, Oman, India and China.<ref>http://m.burtonmail.co.uk/Repton-School-open-satellite-school-India/story-29049140-detail/story.html{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Yet another overseas offshoot was set to open in Bulgaria in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.staffordshire-live.co.uk/news/local-news/repton-school-opening-bulgaria-1859297|title=Repton School set to open new centre in Bulgaria|last=Pridding|first=Beth|date=7 August 2018|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Headmasters==\n{{div col}}\n* Thomas Whitehead (1621\u20131639)<ref name=\"Bigsby\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=68oHAAAAQAAJ][[Robert Bigsby]] ''Historical and Topographical Description of Repton''<span> Woodfall and Kinder 1854</span></ref>\n* Philip Ward (1639\u20131642)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* William Ullock (1642\u20131667)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* Joseph Sedgwicke (1667\u20131672)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* Edward Letherland (1672\u20131681)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* John Doughty (1681\u20131705)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* Edward Abbot (1705\u20131714)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* Thomas Gawton (1714\u20131723)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* William Dudson (1723\u20131724)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* George Fletcher (1724\u20131741)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* William Asteley (1741\u20131767)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* William Prior (1767\u20131779)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/><ref name=\"mons\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reptonchurch.org.uk/Monument.htm|title=Monuments of St Wystan's Church, Repton|website=reptonchurch.org.uk|accessdate=13 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303212148/http://www.reptonchurch.org.uk/Monument.htm|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* William Bagshaw Stevens (1779\u20131800)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/><ref name=\"mons\"/>\n* [[William Boultbee Sleath]] (1800\u20131830)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/><ref name=\"mons\"/>\n* John Heyrick Macaulay (1830\u20131840)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/><ref name=\"mons\"/>\n* Reverend Thomas Williamson Peile (1841\u20131854)\n* Steuart Adolphus Pears (1854\u20131874)\n* Henry Robert Huckin (1874\u20131882)\n* [[William Furneaux]] (1883\u20131900)\n* [[Hubert Burge]] (1900\u20131901)\n* [[Lionel Ford]] (1901\u20131910)|\n* [[William Temple (bishop)|William Temple]] (1910\u20131914)\n* [[Geoffrey Fisher]] (1914\u20131932)<ref name=\"boy\">Dahl, Roald, ''Boy'' {{ISBN|0-435-12300-9}} (hardcover, 1986) (see also ''[[Boy: Tales of Childhood]]'')</ref>\n* [[John Christie (headmaster)|John Christie]] (1932\u20131937)\n* [[Michael Clarke (priest)|H.G. Michael Clarke]] (1937\u20131943)\n* Theodore Lynam Thomas (1944\u20131961)\n* [[John Thorn (headmaster)|John Thorn]] (1961\u20131968)\n* John Gammell (1968\u20131978)\n* [[David Jewell]] (1979\u20131987)\n* Graham E. Jones (1987\u20132003)\n* Robert Holroyd (2003\u20132014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/Repton-School-head-teacher-Robert-Holroyd-step/story-25715824-detail/story.html |title=Repton School head teacher Robert Holroyd has to step down due to 'ill health'|work=Burton Mail|accessdate=13 October 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926144016/http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/Repton-School-head-teacher-Robert-Holroyd-step/story-25715824-detail/story.html|archive-date=26 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Sarah Tennant, (acting head, 2014\u20132016)\n* [[Alastair Land]] (2016\u20132019)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/repton-school-head-harrow-safeguarding-1503167|title=Top public school head leaves to take up new role|date=27 April 2018|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=27 April 2018|issn=0307-1235}}<br>- {{cite web|url=http://www.repton.org.uk/New-Headmaster-Announced|title=New Headmaster Announced|website= |publisher=Repton School|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n* Mark Semmence (from March 2019)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://attain.news/announcements/mr-mark-semmence-appointed-headmaster-at-repton-school|title=Mr Mark Semmence Appointed Headmaster at Repton School|work=Attain|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n[[File:Basil Rathbone in Tovarich trailer.jpg|thumb|[[Basil Rathbone]], an alumnus of the school ]]\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n{{Main|List of Old Reptonians}}\n{{See also|Category:People educated at Repton School}}\nAlumni of Repton School are known as ''[[List of Old Reptonians|Old Reptonians]].''\n\nThey include:\n\n* broadcaster [[Jeremy Clarkson]]; author [[Roald Dahl]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Repton School 'helped inspire Dahl' to write Charlie|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-derbyshire-14896806|accessdate=24 February 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=13 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423090629/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-derbyshire-14896806|archive-date=23 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>;\n* sportsman [[C. B. Fry]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historytoday.com/richard-cavendish/death-cb-fry|title=The Death of C.B. Fry - History Today|website=historytoday.com|access-date=11 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603181750/http://www.historytoday.com/richard-cavendish/death-cb-fry|archive-date=3 June 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>;\n* actor [[Basil Rathbone]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basilrathbone.net/biography/|title=Basil Rathbone, Master of Stage and Screen: Biography|website=basilrathbone.net|access-date=11 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108205420/http://www.basilrathbone.net/biography/|archive-date=8 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>;\n* and engineer [[Adrian Newey]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/racing/top-stories/Newey-giving-shape-to-Red-Bull-dreams/articleshow/10361996.cms |title=Newey giving shape to Red Bull dreams - Times of India |last=Batra |first=Ruhi |website=The Times of India |access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Culture and cultural references ==\n\n\n\nThe \"[[The Stig|Stig]]\" character in [[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]] is said to have been named after the school's pejorative slang term for new boys, a private reference with the producer [[Andy Wilman]], who attended Repton with Clarkson.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Parkinson|first=Justin|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-31907458|title=The Jeremy Clarkson story|date=25 March 2015|accessdate=14 June 2016|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>[[File:Southern 926 Repton (37136522726).jpg|alt=1930s steam locomotive named after the school|thumb|1930s steam locomotive named after the school]]There was a steam locomotive called \"Repton\" named after the school in 1934: Southern Rail, class V, Schools No 926). \n\nThe school's motto, {{lang|la|Porta Vacat Culpa}} (\"the gate is free from blame\"), is a quotation from [[Ovid]]'s {{lang|la|[[Fasti (poem)|Fasti]]}}.<ref>[http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/ovid/ovid.fasti2.shtml Ovid's ''Fasti'', book 2], line 204</ref> \"The gate\" ({{lang|la|Porta}}) refers to the school's arch and, by a [[synecdoche]] of {{lang|la|[[pars pro toto]]}}, the school itself, whilst also being a pun on the name of the school's founder, Sir [[John Port (died 1557)|John Port]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rich|first=E. E.|date=April 1961|title=Pro Pelle Cutem, The Hudson's Bay Company Motto\"]|url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/pageant/06/propellecutem.shtml|journal=Manitoba Pageant|volume=6|number=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/mainlist.html?pgi=head.hist|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222025326/http://www.repton.org.uk/mainlist.html?pgi=head.hist|archivedate=22 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TtgWAQAAIAAJ|title=Derbyshire Archaeological Journal|date=23 February 1987|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThe school has twice, in the 1930s and 1980s respectively, represented the fictional Brookfield School in a [[Goodbye, Mr. Chips (1939 film)|1939 film]] and a 1984 BBC version of ''[[Goodbye, Mr. Chips]].''<ref>[http://www.sundaymercury.net/entertainment-news/film-news/film-reviews/2008/06/19/movies-made-in-the-midlands-66331-21105972/ ''Movies made in the Midlands'']. Retrieved March 2011<br />- ''[http://derbyshire.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/repton-derbyshire-5268/ Repton, Derbyshire]''. Retrieved March 2011</ref> Around 200 pupils were extras in the 1939 film.<ref>[http://www.youandyesterday.com/articles/1930s:_A_year_of_tragedy_and_war_worries \"1930s: A year of tragedy and war worries\"]. Retrieved March 2011</ref> Similarly, pupils appeared as extras in the 1984 BBC version.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n== Royal Visits ==\nThe school has had the following royal visits :\n\n*[[Elizabeth II|HM The Queen]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|HRH Prince Phillip]] made an official visit to the school on 28 March 1957, to mark the 400 year anniversary of the school's establishment. The welcome was led by former headmaster Geoffrey Fisher and the Queen planted a [[mulberry tree]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishpathe.com/video/VLVA9V91Z64TJ4ODWHA29J4KQ6HUW-RTV/query/UK|title=Uk: Royal Visit To Repton, Derbyshire|last=Path\u00e9|first=British|website=www.britishpathe.com|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=UK: ROYAL VISIT TO REPTON, DERBYSHIRE ~ Clip #110164997|url=https://www.pond5.com/stock-footage/item/110164997-uk-royal-visit-repton-derbyshire|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n*[[Katharine, Duchess of Kent|HRH The Duchess of Kent]] visited the school in June 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/news/history/duchess-kent-impressed-crowds-during-147021|title=A Royal visit for Repton in 1985|last=Sinfield|first=Stephen|date=2017-05-19|website=burtonmail|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* The school received a visit from [[Duke of Kent|HRH The Duke of Kent]] in September 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/archive/201309|title=September 2013|website=The Royal Family|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* The school marked its 450th anniversary in 2007 with a royal visit from [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|HRH Prince Edward]].\n\n== Social action ==\n[[File:Swimming 4x100m freestyle relay 2017-08-07 09.jpg|thumb|Adam Peaty attended Repton School after his talent was identified  ]]\nIn May 2016, the school made [[defibrillator]]s on its site available to the local community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/Repton-villagers-access-defibrillators/story-29261534-detail/story.html|title=Repton villagers give access to two defibrillators|date=12 May 2016|website=Burton Mail|accessdate=27 May 2016}} {{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Some of the staff at the school have been vocal about the issue of [[Traffic ticket|speeding]] traffic in the village of [[Repton]] and have participated in public [[Radar gun|speed gun]] enforcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Campaigners-Repton-Milton-gunning-speeders/story-11580107-detail/story.html|title=Campaigners from Repton and Milton gunning for speeders|date=10 July 2008|website=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=28 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008030618/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/campaigners-repton-milton-gunning-speeders/story-11580107-detail/story.html|archivedate=8 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe school's facilities are used by the wider community from time to time. The Olympic gold medal and world record holder [[Adam Peaty]] used Repton's swimming pool as a training facility. His coach, Melanie Marshall, teaches swimming at the school.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/aug/08/adam-peaty-swimming-club-celebrates-success |title='He's our hero': Adam Peaty's swimming club celebrates his success |first1=Josh |last1=Halliday |first2=Haroon |last2=Siddique |date=8 August 2016 |accessdate=13 October 2017 |newspaper=The Guardian |location= London}}</ref>\n\n== The old priory  ==\nRepton Priory was a 12th-century [[Augustinian]] foundation. It was dissolved in 1538. After dissolution, the Thacker family lived at the priory until 1553.  One of this family, Gilbert Thacker, destroyed the church, almost entirely in a day; he did this during the time of Queen [[Mary I of England|Mary]], fearing the priory would be recommissioned as part of the [[Counter-Reformation]]. <ref name=\"Page\">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=40125 \"Houses of Austin canons: The priory of Repton, with the cell of Calke\"], ''A History of the County of Derby'', volume 2 (1907), pp. 58\u201363. Retrieved 8 June 2013</ref><ref name=\"Rep\"> {{cite web |url=http://www.reptonchurch.org.uk/index.htm |title=Repton Church: Our Church \u2013 Christianity in Repton |accessdate=9 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618152029/http://www.reptonchurch.org.uk/index.htm |archivedate=18 June 2013  }}</ref>[[File:Arch and Old Priory, Repton - geograph.org.uk - 273607.jpg|right|thumb|The School Arch, formerly part of [[Repton Priory]], was moved to its current site in 1906.<ref name=\"PS\" />]]Only parts of the original buildings remained when the school was established. These comprised:<ref name=list>{{cite web|title=Remains of Priory Church|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-82775-remains-of-priory-church-and-the-chapter-|website=British Listed Buildings|accessdate=8 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=PS>{{PastScape|mnumber=1058695 |mname= PRIORY GATEWAY|accessdate=11 June 2013}}</ref>the footings of areas of the priory remain in some areas, uncovered during construction work in 1922; the bases of a cluster of columns of the former chancel and chapels; fragments of an arch belonging to the former [[pulpitum]], moved to their current position in 1906;<ref name=\"PS\" /> fragments of the door surrounds of both the [[chapter house]] and warming room.<ref name=\"list\" /><ref name=\"pastc\">{{PastScape|mname=Repton|mnumber=313097|accessdate=11 June 2013}}</ref> and largest surviving portion of the priory known as \"Prior Overton's Tower\", which is post 1437; largely altered, it has been incorporated into a 19th-century building.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1057669 |desc =Repton Hall with Prior Overton's Tower, Repton School|accessdate=11 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:NewHouseRepton.JPG|New House\nImage:ReptonThrotheArch.JPG|The Arch\nImage:Repton School, Repton - geograph.org.uk - 1650810.jpg|The Old Priory and Garth\nImage:Repton School - geograph.org.uk - 1303684.jpg|Pears School\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Repton School}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.repton.org.uk/}}\n* [http://www.foremarke.org.uk/ Repton Preparatory School website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141125142242/http://www.repton.org.uk/old-reptonian-society Old Reptonian Society]\n* [http://www.reptondubai.org/ Repton Dubai website]\n* [http://www.isbi.com/isbi-viewschool/1508-REPTON_SCHOOL.html ISBI Information on Repton School]\n\n\n{{Derbyshire Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Independent schools in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Repton School|*]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Schools cricket]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1550s]]\n[[Category:1557 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{For|the school of the same name in Dubai|Repton School Dubai}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Repton School\n | logo                    = Reptoncrest.png\n | image                   = ReptonSchool2007.JPG\n | alt                     = \n | caption                 = \n | motto                   = {{Lang-la|Porta Vacat Culpa}}\n | motto_translation       = The gate is free from blame\n | address                 = [[Repton]]\n | city                    = \n | county                  = [[Derbyshire]]\n | postcode                = DE65 6FH\n | country                 = England\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|52.8409|-1.5510|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n | other_name              = <!-- or | other_names = -->\n | former_name             = <!-- or | former_names = -->\n | type                    = [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|Independent]], [[Day school|day]] and boarding school\n | religious_affiliation   = Christian\n | established             = {{Unbulleted list|''Bequest made:'' {{Start date|df=y|1557}}|''Land acquired:'' 1559}}\n | founder                 = [[John Port (died 1557)|Sir John Port]]\n | closed                  = \n | local_authority         = [[Derbyshire County Council]]\n | trust                   = \n | urn                     = 113009\n | ofsted                  = \n | headmaster              = Mark Semmence<ref>/https://www.repton.org.uk/about-repton/welcome-from-the-head</ref>\n | staff                   = \n | gender                  = [[Mixed-sex education|Mixed]]\n | age_range               = 13\u201318\n | enrolment               = 635 (2020)<ref name=\"GOV.UK\">{{cite web |title=Repton School |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Establishments/Establishment/Details/113009 |website=Get information about schools |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom |accessdate=26 March 2019 }}</ref>\n | capacity                = 680<ref name=\"GOV.UK\" />\n | campus_size             = \n | campus_type             = \n | houses                  = [[#Houses and pastoral arrangements|10]]\n | colours                 = Navy and yellow\n | accreditation           = <!-- or | accreditations = -->\n | publication             = \n | yearbook                = \n | affiliation             = <!-- or | affiliations = -->\n | alumni                  = [[#Old Reptonians|Old Reptonians]]\n | free_label              = Preparatory school\n | free_text               = [[Repton Preparatory School]]\n | website                 = {{URL|repton.org.uk}}\n | footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Repton School''' is a [[Mixed-sex education|mixed]] co-educational [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] school, for pupils from ages 13 to 18, in [[Repton]], [[Derbyshire]], England, United Kingdom. The school was [[Single-sex education|boys only]] until girls were admitted to the [[sixth form]] early in the 1970s, and by the 1990s it was fully [[Mixed-sex education|co-educational]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Mike|title=Exploring the village of Repton \u2013 one of South Derbyshire's gems|url=http://www.derbyshirelife.co.uk/out-about/places/exploring_the_village_of_repton_one_of_south_derbyshire_s_gems_1_4225773|website=Derbyshire Life|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:JohnPortKright.jpg|left|thumb|Brass of Sir John Port on his tomb in St Helen's parish church, [[Etwall]], Derbyshire. He founded Repton School.]]\n\n===Origins===\nThe school was founded by a 1557 legacy in the will of Sir [[John Port (died 1557)|John Port]] of [[Etwall]], leaving funds for a grammar school at [[Etwall]] or Repton, condition on the students praying daily for the souls of his family.<ref name=\"JP\">{{cite ODNB|title=John Port|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/22552|accessdate=11 June 2013|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/22552|year=2004}}</ref>\n\nBuildings at the site of Repton Priory were granted for the school in 1559 by Gilbert Thacker. Not long after this, lawsuits began between the school and the Thacker family. These focused on access issues, <ref name=\"Records\">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/recordsandremin00messgoog/recordsandremin00messgoog_djvu.txt|title=Records and Reminiscences of Repton|website=archive.org|accessdate=31 May 2016}}</ref> and relations with the Thackers deteriorated to the extent that that, by the 1650s, the school and the family were embroiled in litigation:  the school commenced an action against the Thacker family in 1642; the family also brought an action against the school which was settled out of court. The atmosphere around the conflict was sufficiently aggressive that the Thackers diverted drains into the school's buildings by constructing dams, and in 1670, a wall was built to keep the parties apart.<ref name=\"Records\" />\n\nA pupil's letter home in 1728 relates to his father that the headmaster, George Fletcher, would withhold meals from the boys if they were unable to recite scripture.<ref name=\"Records\" /> \n\nPupil numbers swung between 80 and 200 in the first hundred years, but as the school was free until 1768 it is unclear how teaching was afforded. \n\nThe headmaster kept cattle in a room within the school around this period.<ref name=\"Records\" />\n\n=== Decline ===\n\nThe school's reputation and operation declined in the 1700s and the 1800s, and pupil numbers were under 50 by 1833, with a former pupil recalled after leaving:<blockquote>\n\"even more than the paucity of its numbers, was the almost total absence of all those facilities... cricket ground we had none. Football was played upon the gravel, between the Arch, and the broken pillars...No gymnasium, no fives court, no racquet court...No French, no German, no Music, no Natural Science... No chapel, no master's house beyond the Arch, no bridge (at first) across the Trent, no railway.... Why did even 50 boys resort to Sir John Port's old School?\"<ref name=Records/>\n</blockquote>\nAlthough by the 1830s some of the changes of reforming schoolmaster of [[Rugby School|Rugby Schoo]]<nowiki/>l Dr. [[Thomas Arnold]] were being implemented at the school,<ref name=Records/> the school declined further in the following decades.[[File:Repton Grammar School, Repton, Derbyshire; gateway. Tinted l Wellcome V0014398.jpg|alt=Repton Grammar School, Repton, Derbyshire: gateway. Tinted lithograph by Hullmandel & Walton|thumb|Repton Grammar School gateway: tinted [[lithograph]] by [[Charles Joseph Hullmandel|Hullmandel & Walton]]|left]]The decline was stopped by headmaster Steuart Pears, who worked hard to raise the school's status and reputation.{{cn|date=February 2020}} A major effort was made, with the [[Charity Commission for England and Wales|Charity Commissioners]] and the [[Clarendon Commission]], to have the school accepted as one of the great public schools.<ref name=\"Records\" /> Repton was excluded from their 1864 report, however, which included only nine schools, and the school was thus excluded from the [[Public Schools Act 1868]] and hence the status of being a [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public school]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.educationengland.org.uk/documents/acts/1868-public-schools-act.html|title=Text of the Public Schools Act, 1868|date=17 February 2013|website=Education in England|publisher=Derek Gillard|access-date=31 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the early centuries of the school's development, a pupil-conferred role called \"Cock of the School\" was accepted within the pupil body, a boy would be identified as the holder of this office after fighting between likely candidates. \n\nOnce a boy was incumbent in this role, the younger boys were regarded as his slaves and customarily required to defer to him and to do his work; writing in 1907, G. S. Messiter described the practice as an \"ancient custom\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=George Stephen Messiter|url=https://archive.org/details/recordsandremin00messgoog|title=Records and Reminiscences of Repton|date=1907|publisher=A.J. Lawrence|others=Harvard University|page=[https://archive.org/details/recordsandremin00messgoog/page/n52 41]}}</ref>\n\n===Recovery===\n[[File:Repton School Chapel - geograph.org.uk - 273610.jpg|thumb|Repton School Chapel|alt=]]\nIn 1884 a chapel was added to the school's buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-82781-the-chapel-repton-school-repton-derbyshir|title=The Chapel, Repton School, Repton, Derbyshire|website=British Listed Buildings|access-date=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nA number of headmasters of Repton went on to senior Church of England positions in the twentieth century. Dr. Furneaux was headmaster from 1882 to 1900, and, after retiring from Repton, he became [[Dean of Winchester]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.winchester-cathedral.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/Safe-Sound-and-Secure.pdf|title=Winchester Cathedral: Safe, Sound, and Secure: A Centenary Tribute to William Walker the Diver |last=Farthing |first=David |website=Winchester Cathedral |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Lionel Ford]] was headmaster from 1901\u20131910, and he went on to be [[Dean of York]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1349397/Neville-Ford.html|title=Neville Ford|journal=Daily Telegraph|date=2000-07-19|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>  [[Hubert Burge]] was headmaster between 1900 and 1901, after leaving the school he would become [[Bishop of Oxford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxford.anglican.org/who-we-are/history-of-the-diocese/bishops-of-oxford/|title=List of Bishops of Oxford since 1542|website=Diocese of Oxford|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[William Temple (bishop)|William Temple]] was headmaster for four years from 1910 to 1914, and he went on to become [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] in 1942.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spartacus-educational.com/REtempleW.htm|title=William Temple|website=Spartacus Educational|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nRecent research published in ''Picturing the closet: male secrecy and homosexual visibility in Britain,'' by Dominic Janes, found that between 1900 and 1914, the \"Black Book\" (the school discipline record) recorded 38 instances of immorality within the pupil community; punishments for this activity ranged from caning to expulsion,<ref name=\"DJ\">{{Cite book|title=Picturing the closet : male secrecy and homosexual visibility in Britain|last=Dominic.|first=Janes|isbn=9780190205638|location=New York|oclc=884665212|year = 2015}}</ref> most of the activity was performed in groups, with Janes concluding \"what we are seeing here is [not] the victimisation of couples, but the periodic purges of small cadres of peers\".<ref name=\"DJ\" /> Immediately after this period, when [[Geoffrey Fisher]] became headmaster in 1914, an account was as follows: \"homosexuality was rife. Fisher immediately expelled two senior boys and began to rule with a very firm hand\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=The bishops|last=Trevor.|first=Beeson|date=2002|publisher=SCM Press|isbn=9780334029168|location=London|oclc=59450207}}</ref>  Fisher would go on to become [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], but his tenure as headmaster has been linked to \"blithe.. extraordinary violence and psychological cruelty\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Renton|first=Alex|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/apr/08/school-boarding-secrets-crimes-alex-renton-kipling-rowling-dahl-churchill|title=School of hard knocks: the dark underside to boarding school books|date=2017-04-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[File:Harold Abrahams 1924.jpg|alt=Harold Abrahams, joined the school in 1914|thumb|[[Harold Abrahams]], pictured here at the 1924 Olympics, joined the school in 1914]][[Harold Abrahams]] CBE, the Olympic champion in the 100m sprint in the 1924 Paris Olympics, depicted in the 1981 film ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'', joined the school in 1914. Recalling his time at the school, Abrahams said he encountered [[antisemitism]], often feeling [[Bullying|bullied]] and alone.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PCpTBgAAQBAJ|title=Sneaker Century: A History of Athletic Shoes|last=Keyser|first=Amber J.|date=1 January 2015|publisher=Twenty-First Century Books|isbn=9781467763097}}</ref>\n\nIn 1907 a gymnasium was added. This building is now grade II listed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-82782-gymnasium-and-attached-gates-repton-schoo|title=Gymnasium and Attached Gates, Repton School, Repton, Derbyshire|first=Good|last=Stuff|website=British Listed Buildings |accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> In this decade the chapel was enlarged, and the Science Block, the Gymnasium, Armoury, Shooting Range and Swimming Bath were built, and the Priory \u2018Tithe\u2019 Barn turned into the Art School.<ref>{{Cite book|last=The Central Education Co. Ltd|title=Repton School, an introductory booklet|publisher=The Central Education Co. Ltd|year=1959|isbn=|location=Derby|pages=51}}</ref>\n\nA reforming master, [[Victor Gollancz]], established evening class in political education for the boys in the early 1900s. The school considered that this tended to \"undermine the authority of the teachers by encouraging the pupils to ask questions and work with the boys in a colaborative<!--sic?--> way\", so he was termed a \"traitor\" and a \"pacifist\" and was dismissed form the school.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=E6uoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT302&lpg=PT302&dq=repton+school+corporal+punishment#v=onepage&q=repton%20school&f=false|title=Public School Literature, Civic Education and the Politics of Male Adolescence|last=Holt|first=Jenny|date=2016 |publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351907668}}</ref>\n\n1,912 former pupils of the school served in the [[First World War]], of whom 355 died in service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.repton.org.uk/great-war-exhibition|title=Great War Exhibition|website=repton.org.uk|access-date=2 July 2016}}</ref> A war memorial was added to the school's site in 1921.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-82776-war-memorial-at-repton-school-repton-derb|title=War Memorial at Repton School \u2013 Repton \u2013 Derbyshire \u2013 England |website=British Listed Buildings|last=Stuff|first=Good |accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1917 the writers [[Christopher Isherwood]] and [[Edward Upward]] began their time at Repton. They formed a friendship which continued when they both at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]. They revolted at school against everything associated with the establishment, which they called \"the other side\", and Upward reflected after leaving that \"everyone was homosexual, up to a point, at Repton\". <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/4192502/Hello-to-Berlin-boys-and-books.html|title=Hello to Berlin, boys and books|journal=The Daily Telegraph|date=27 May 2004|accessdate=5 August 2018|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> In the 1920s, the poet [[Vernon Watkins]] was sent to Repton. His gentle character provoked regular bullying in his early years. When he died, the school claimed him as \"perhaps the best poet Repton has had\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/templates/article.jsp?articleid=58903&back=|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, \"Vernon Watkins\" entry|last=Watkins|first=Meic|year=2004|website=Oxford DNB|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=31 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe writer and painter [[Denton Welch]] was a pupil in the 1930s, and his account of running away from the school, subsequent return and miserable final term there is first part of his autobiographical novel ''[[Maiden Voyage (novel)|Maiden Voyage]]'' (1943).\n\nIn 1924 George Gilbert Stocks, a director of music at the school, set it to the hymn ''Dear Lord and Father of Mankind'' to the tune ''Repton'' for use in the school's chapel.  He took the melody from [[Hubert Parry]]'s  1888 contralto aria \"Long since in Egypt's plenteous land\" in his oratorio ''Judith''. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://timelyscores.com/2017/07/20/repton-rest-hymn-tunes/|title=Dear Lord and Father of Mankind|date=20 July 2017|accessdate=13 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014034317/https://timelyscores.com/2017/07/20/repton-rest-hymn-tunes/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Roald Dahl (1982).jpg|alt=Roald Dahl gives accounts of his time at Repton in his book 'Boy'|thumb|150px|[[Roald Dahl]] gives accounts of his time at Repton in his autobiography]]\n\nThe writer [[Roald Dahl]] attended in the 1930s. His experiences are related in his semi-autobiographical book ''[[Boy (book)|Boy]]'', in which he describes an environment of ritual cruelty, [[fagging]] and [[School corporal punishment|beatings]], later stating \"I was appalled by the fact that masters and senior boys were allowed literally to wound other boys, and sometimes quite severely... I couldn't get over it. I never have got over it.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Briggs|first=Julia|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GCWoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT410&lpg=PT410&dq=I+was+appalled+by+the+fact+that+masters+and+senior+boys+were+allowed+literally+to+wound+other+boys,+and+sometimes+quite+severely...+I+couldn't+get+over+it.+I+never+have+got+over+it#v=onepage|title=Popular Children's Literature in Britain|last2=Butts|first2=Dennis|date=2016-12-05|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-351-91003-3|language=en}}</ref> An account of a beating of boy called Micheal, in [[Roald Dahl|Roald Dahl's]] 1984 autobiographical book ''[[Boy (book)|Boy]]'',{{NoteTag|\"... he was ordered to take down his trousers and kneel on the headmaster\u2019s sofa with the top half of his body hanging over one end of the sofa. The great man then gave him one terrific crack. After that there was a pause. The cane was put down and the headmaster began filling his pipe from a tin of tobacco. He also started to lecture the kneeling boy about sin and wrongdoing. Soon, the cane was picked up again and a second tremendous crack was administered upon the trembling buttocks. Then the pipe-filling business and the lecture went on for maybe 30 seconds. Then came the third crack of the cane ... At the end of it all, a basin, a sponge and a small clean towel were produced by the headmaster, and the victim was told to wash away the blood before pulling up his trousers.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Roald |last=Dahl |authorlink=Roald Dahl |title=Boy |title-link=Boy (book) |year=1984 |publisher=[[Jonathan Cape|Cape]]}}</ref>}} was attributed by Dahl to Fisher. But Dahl's biographer, [[Jeremy Treglown]], has pointed out he was mistaken: the beating was in May 1933, a year after Fisher had left Repton, and headmaster concerned was [[John Christie (headmaster)|John Christie]], Fisher's successor.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Treglown|first1=Jeremy|authorlink1=Jeremy Treglown|title=Roald Dahl: a Biography|location=London | publisher=Faber & Faber|year=1994 |isbn=978-0-571-16573-5 |page=21}}</ref>\n\n=== Second World War and after ===\nThe headmaster from 1937 to 1943 was [[Michael Clarke (priest)|H.G. Michael Clarke]], he left the school to pursue an eclisiastical career and became [[Dean of Birmingham Cathedral|Provost of Birmingham Cathedral]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F39304|title=The Discovery Service|last=Archives|first=The National|website=discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> He led the school during one of the most difficult periods of its history, when mounting debts and falling numbers, together with the effects of the war, led to questions as to the continuing viability of the institution; Clarke was obliged to close departments and two houses (The Cross and Latham).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hillman|first=Nicholas|authorlink=Nick Hillman|date=1 December 2010|title=The Public Schools Commission: 'Impractical, Expensive and Harmful to Children'?|journal=Contemporary British History|volume=24|issue=4|pages=511\u2013531|doi=10.1080/13619462.2010.518413|issn=1361-9462}}</ref> The school owed \u00a350,000 (around \u00a33.5 million at today's prices) and, in 1941, the [[Ministry of Education (United Kingdom)|Board of Education]] said its \"future is doubtful\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hillman|first=Nicholas|authorlink=Nick Hillman|date=1 December 2010|title=The Public Schools Commission: 'Impractical, Expensive and Harmful to Children'?|journal=Contemporary British History|volume=24|issue=4|pages=511\u2013531|doi=10.1080/13619462.2010.518413|issn=1361-9462}}</ref> \n\nThe total number of pupils was 353 at the outbreak of war, which fell to 273 in 1943. Numbers recovered in the late 1940s, and The Cross was able to reopen in 1945 and Latham House in 1947. By 1957, the school was in better health, and was full with 470 pupils.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hillman|first=Nick|authorlink=Nick Hillman|year=2012|title=Repton and the HMC during the Second World War |url=http://www.johncatt.com/downloads/pdf/magazines/ccr/ccr49_1/ccr49_1.pdf|journal=Conference & Common Room|volume=49|issue=1|access-date=19 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the Second World War, 188 former members of the school died serving in the armed forces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ww1-yorkshires.org.uk/html-files/repton-school.htm|title=The Yorkshire Regiment, Local War Memorials|website=ww1-yorkshires.org.uk|accessdate=3 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n1957 saw the 400 year centenary of the school, celebrated with a Royal visit from The Queen and Duke of Edinburgh.  A new Chemistry Block and new workshops within the Precinct, as well as extensive alterations to the Science Block.  John Gammell took office as headmaster in 1968 and during his tenure girls began to be educated at Repton. It started with the arrival of two girls in 1970. By 1979 the first purpose-built girls\u2019 boarding house was opened.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Plowright|first=John|title=Repton to the end|publisher=Third Millennium Publishin|year=2007|isbn=166382208|location=London|pages=28}}</ref>\n[[File:Jeremy Clarkson 2008.jpg|thumb|Jeremy Clarkson attended Repton in the 1970s. ]]\nFagging is recorded as having taken place at Repton into the late 20th century.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Roach|first=Martin|title=The Top Gear Story \u2013 The 100% Unofficial Story of the Most Famous Car Show... In The World|publisher=John Blake Publishing|year=2014|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref> Jeremy Clarkson noted after leaving that, \"I suffered many terrible things. I was thrown on an hourly basis into the ice plunge pool, dragged from my bed in the middle of the night and beaten, made to lick the lavatories clean and all the usual humiliations that... turn a small boy into a gibbering, sobbing, suicidal wreck... they glued my records together, snapped my compass, ate my biscuits, defecated in my tuck box and they cut my trousers in half\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/celebrity/clarkson-was-suicidal-at-school-after-being-bullied/ar-AAbWf5j|title=Clarkson was suicidal at school after being bullied|date=2016-06-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605073627/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/celebrity/clarkson-was-suicidal-at-school-after-being-bullied/ar-AAbWf5j|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-date=5 June 2016}}</ref>  In the 1980s. [[Chris Adams (cricketer)|Chris Adams]] was at the school and subsequently observed, \"The ingrained hierarchy whereby the older boys would subject the younger pupils to a lot of misery through the system of fagging. It was basically a system of slavery and I hated seeing the young lads literally trembling with fear\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Chris|first=Adams|title=Grizzly : my life and times in cricket|date=2015-10-14|isbn=9781785311239|location=Durrington|oclc=949931533}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1980s, the old [[Sanatorium]] was converted into a Music School.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Plowright|first=John|title=Repton to the End.|publisher=Third Millennium|year=2007|isbn=166382208|location=London|pages=41}}</ref>  Another fall in numbers in the 1990s required Graham Jones, headmaster from 1987 to 2003, to close two boys boarding houses -- Brook House and The Hall -- taking their occupants and forming a new house, School House.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Plowright|first=John|title=Repton to the end|date=2007|isbn=978-1-903942-55-0|language=English|oclc=166382208}}</ref>\n\n=== 21st century ===\n[[File:Repton School Business Centre and Gallery. - geograph.org.uk - 898867.jpg|thumb|Repton School Business Centre and Gallary, in a former shop]]\nThe school marked its 450th anniversary in 2007 with a royal visit from [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|HRH Prince Edward]].  Celebrations also included concerts featuring [[Michael Ball]] and [[Bryan Ferry]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Plowright|first=John|title=Repton to the end|publisher=Third Millennium Publishing|year=2007|isbn=166382208|location=London|pages=165}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 the 1957 400 Hall theatre was remodelled, by [[Avery Associates Architects]],<ref>{{cite web |title=400 Hall Theatre AJ Buildings Library |url=https://www.ajbuildingslibrary.co.uk/projects/display/id/6917 |website=www.ajbuildingslibrary.co.uk |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref> following a \u00a33.3 million upgrade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-15753674|title=Repton School theatre reopens after \u00a33.3m revamp|date=16 November 2011|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 August 2017}}</ref> In 2013 a \u00a39&nbsp;million science block was built. During the preparations for the building work, archaeological digs were undertaken which indicated the site had been occupied in the [[Roman Britain|Roman period]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repton.org.uk/Royal-Opening-for-Reptons-Science-Priory|title=Royal Opening for Repton's Science Priory|website=|publisher=Repton|accessdate=13 October 2017}}<br>- {{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Discovery-Roman-past-real-life-school-history/story-16902012-detail/story.html|title=Discovery of Roman past is a real-life school history lesson|date=14 September 2012|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=8 June 2016}} {{Dead link|date=August 2018|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>  Around this time, the old [[Squash (sport)|Squash Courts]] were made into a new gallery and textiles studio for the Art department.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Plowright|first=John|title=Repton to the End|publisher=Third Millennium|year=2007|isbn=166382208|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe period 2015-2019 saw some rapid cycling of leadership of the school. Nevertheless, a new teaching block, the Lynam Thomas Building, in the Precinct and a major refurbishment programme being undertaken.  In November 2019 [[Adam Peaty]] opened a newly redeveloped \u00a36m sports centre at the school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/news/2019-11-21/Repton-School-Sports-Centre-opened-by-Olympian-Adam-Peaty-MBE|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> Alastair Land was headmaster from 2016 to 2019, leaving to become headmaster at [[Harrow School|Harrow]], and was succeeded as Headmaster by Mark Semmence.\n\nIn November 2019, [[Libby Lane|Revd Libby Lane]], [[Bishop of Derby|Lord Bishop of Derby]] (the first female bishop in the Church of England) was appointed Visitor of Repton School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/news/2019-11-04/Bishop-of-Derby-appointed-Visitor-of-Repton-School|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2020 it was announced that the school would be merging with [[Foremarke Hall]] School from September 2020.<ref name=\"derbytelegraph\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/burton/two-derbyshire-schools-merge-3758103|title=These two Derbyshire schools are to merge|date=2020-01-20|work=derbytelegraph|access-date=2020-01-24|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Shortly after, St Wystan's School announced it was exploratory talks to join Repton.<ref name=\"derbytelegraph\" />\n\n== Fees and inspection ==\nIn 2019/20, fees were \u00a336,783 for boarders and \u00a327,207 for day pupils per year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/admissions/fees|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nThere are scholarships available for drama, sport, art, music, academic capacity and \"all-rounder talent\"; these do not exceed 20% of the school's fees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/admissions/scholarships-bursaries|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>  There is also some bursary assistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repton.org.uk/scholarships-bursaries|title=Scholarships & Bursaries |website= |publisher=Repton School |accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe school is inspected by the [[Independent Schools Inspectorate]]. An integrated inspection took place in March 2014, finding the school to be \"exceptionally successful in achieving its aims... the quality of the pupils' achievements is excellent\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isi.net/school/repton-school-6835|title=March 2014 ISI Inspection|website= |publisher=ISI}}</ref>\n\nAn emergency inspection in January 2015 was ordered by the [[Department for Education]] reviewing welfare and safeguarding compliance under the Independent School Standard Regulations (ISSRs) and the National Minimum Standards for Boarding (NMSB). The school failed to meet these national minimum standards at that inspection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://isischools.devprocess.com/DownloadReport.aspx?t=c&r=FLWEV6835_20150121.pdf&s=6835|title=Emergency Inspection 2015|last=Independent Schools Inspectorate|website=|publisher=Independent Schools Inspectorate|access-date=5 August 2015}}</ref> \n\nA regulatory Compliance Inspection took place in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isi.net/school/repton-school-6835?results=true|title=Repton School :: Independent Schools Inspectorate|website=www.isi.net|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> \n\n== Houses and pastoral arrangements ==\nA little over two-thirds of pupils are boarders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukboardingschools.com/schools/repton-school/|title=Repton School|date=16 July 2013|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> Former houses that have renamed or redeveloped include: The Hall (at one time divided into A-K and L-Z) \u2013 now known as School House; and Brook House.\n\nThe school currently has 10 houses: six for boys and four for girls:\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* The Abbey (girls)\n* The Cross (boys)\n* Field House (girls)\n* The Garden (girls)\n* Latham House (boys)\n* The Mitre (girls)\n* New House (boys)\n* The Orchard (boys)\n* The Priory (boys)\n* School House (boys)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/boarding-houses/house-life-pastoral-care|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Sports and clubs==\n[[File:Bunny Austin (1936).jpg|thumb|[[Bunny Austin]] attended Repton School. ]]\nThe school competes in various sports,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.repton.org.uk/sport2|title=Repton School Sport|website=repton.org.uk|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> its focus sports are: football (winter), hockey (spring), cricket (summer) for boys; and hockey (winter), netball (spring), tennis (summer) for girls, and swimming through the year for both genders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/sport/focus-sports|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> \n\nNotable sporting former pupils include the 1932 Wimbledon tennis finalist, [[Bunny Austin]], and several first-class cricketers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reptonpilgrims.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=55:repton-school-1st-class-cricketers&catid=37:1st-class-cricketers&Itemid=60|title=Repton Pilgrims Cricket Club|website=Repton Pilgrims Cricket Club|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2013, six former pupils played together in an international hockey match.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/hockey/10478137/Repton-School-claim-hockey-history-as-six-former-pupils-play-in-GB-v-Germany-series.html |title=Repton School claim hockey history as six former pupils play in GB v Germany series |first=Rod |last=Gilmour |date=27 November 2013 |accessdate=13 October 2017 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location= London}}</ref> \n\nThe school has a [[Combined Cadet Force]] and a music school, as well as various after-school clubs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.repton.org.uk/extra-curricular |title=StackPath |access-date=16 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520125118/http://www.repton.org.uk/extra-curricular |archive-date=20 May 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  [[Adam Peaty]], the Olympic swimmer, attended the school for a period on a scholarship after his potential was identified.\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Sexual abuse ===\n\nThe Charity Commission received a number of safeguarding-related serious incident reports from Repton School in February 2018, and it commented \"[i]ncidents of this nature are of serious concern\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/repton-school-allegations-charity-commission-1394332|title=Repton School regulator has 'serious concern' over safeguarding incidents|date=1 April 2018|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=7 April 2018|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Incidents leading to this included:\n\n* A former head of physics, John Mitchell, who was found to have abused a position of trust contrary to s.16(1)(a) of the [[Sexual Offences Act 2003]] on 6 December 2014 when he engaged in sexual activity with a female between the age of 13 and 17 and he did not believe that she was 18 or over. He also communicated in a sexual way and with sexual motivations to this same pupil. He was disqualified from teaching indefinitely by the [[National College for Teaching and Leadership]], following a finding that this was unacceptable professional conduct.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/506803/Web_decision_-_John_Mitchell.pdf|title=Mr John Mitchell: Professional conduct panel outcome|date=2 March 2016|website=|publisher=National College for Teaching and Leadership|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref>\n* In October 2017 a former pupil began proceedings against the school, claiming negligence on the school's part, in connection with an alleged [[rape]] of that pupil by another pupil in 2014, when a 17-year-old pupil was arrested on suspicion of carrying out two rapes at the school;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/teenager-arrested-over-two-rape-allegations-at-jeremy-clarkson-s-old-private-school-9890012.html|title=Teenager arrested over two rape allegations at Jeremy Clarkson's old private school|date=28 November 2017|work=The Independent|accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> in this action it is understood that it was claimed that the school failed to supervise or discipline its pupil. The claimant made a request of the Derbyshire Constabulary for the papers from its investigation, which the police refused to provide without a court order.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boardingconcern.org.uk/2017/10/09/repton-school-sued-failing-protect-pupil-rapist/|title=Repton School sued for failing to protect pupil from a 'rapist'|date=9 October 2017|work=Boarding Concern|accessdate=7 April 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408011010/https://www.boardingconcern.org.uk/2017/10/09/repton-school-sued-failing-protect-pupil-rapist/|archive-date=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n* In 2018 four members of the school's staff were subject to police investigation for inappropriate sexual conduct towards children.  In August 2018, one of these individuals, Jeremy Woodside, a 28-year-old former organist at the school, was placed on the [[Sex offender registry|Sex Offender's Register]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/repton-school-sex-offenders-register-1857939|title=Former Repton School staff member placed on sex offenders' register|date=3 August 2018|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=5 August 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804120309/https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/repton-school-sex-offenders-register-1857939|archive-date=4 August 2018|issn=0307-1235}} </ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/crime/106206341/christchurch-pianist-on-british-sex-offender-register|title=Christchurch pianist on British sex offender register|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> The chronology of those issues emerging in early 2018 was as follows: \n** on 29 January, 2018, police arrested a member of staff on suspicion of attempting [[Child sexual abuse|sexual contact with a child]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/repton-school-arrest-child-sex-1203554|title=Repton School staff member accused of attempting sexual contact with child|date=14 February 2018|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=18 March 2018|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n** on 14 March, 2018, a second police investigation into a staff member, relating to safeguarding concerns, was launched;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Crowson|first=Isaac|url=https://www.burtonmail.co.uk/news/local-news/shock-second-former-repton-school-1310427|title=Another former staff member at Repton School under investigation|date=14 March 2018|work=Burton Mail|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n**on 26 March, 2018 allegations against a further two members of staff were reported.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/repton-school-allegations-against-staff-1376483|title=Repton School: allegations made about two more staff members|date=2018-03-26|work=derbytelegraph|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, a 53-year-old former teacher appeared in court after being charged with a number of sex offences against underage girls, including [[indecent assault]] and [[gross indecency]] with a child. The offences are alleged to have taken place in the 1990s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/trial-date-moved-case-ex-3666586|title=Trial date moved in case of ex-Repton teacher accused of sex offences|date=2019-12-23|work=derbytelegraph|access-date=2020-01-04|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/former-teacher-charged-indecently-assaulting-2744842|title=Former teacher charged with indecently assaulting pupils at school|date=10 April 2019|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=21 April 2019|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He will stand trial for 11 charges in December 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/ex-repton-teacher-pleads-not-2860403|title=Ex-Repton teacher pleads not guilty to indecent assaults on underage girls|date=13 May 2019|newspaper=Derby Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n=== Incidents ===\nIn 2014, Southern Derbyshire Magistrates\u2019 Court fined the school \u00a310,000 following a guilty plea to a health and safety charge after an incident of negligence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cqms-ltd.co.uk/derbyshire-school-fined-after-grandmother-falls-from-stairs/|title=Derbyshire school fined after grandmother falls from stairs|last=QCMS|date=|website=QCMS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In April 2019, a teacher tested positive for drink-driving after police saw his vehicle mount a kerb and then enter the school grounds. He was subsequently convicted and banned from driving for 20 months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/repton-school-teacher-england-hockey-2725962|title=Repton school teacher and England hockey ace caught drink-driving|date=7 April 2019|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=21 April 2019|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Two months later a chemical spillage at the school's sports centre resulted in nine individuals needing precautionary treatment, as a result of a chlorine leak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/nine-treated-following-chemical-spill-3017399|title=Nine treated following chemical spill at top Derbyshire school|website=Derbyshire Telegraph|accessdate=24 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Fee fixing and gender pay gap===\nIn September 2005, the school was one of fifty independent schools operating [[Independent school fee fixing scandal|independent school fee-fixing]], in breach of the [[Competition Act 1998|Competition Act, 1998]]. All of the schools involved were ordered to abandon this practice, pay a nominal penalty of \u00a310,000 each and to make ex-gratia payments totalling three million pounds into a trust designed to benefit pupils who attended the schools during the period in respect of which fee information had been shared.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Halpin |first=Halpin |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/independent-schools-face-huge-fines-over-cartel-to-fix-fees-rcwcznjnvnt |title=Independent schools face huge fines over cartel to fix fees |access-date=2020-02-29 |issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20100402135855tf_/http://www.oft.gov.uk/news/press/2006/182-06|title=Office of Fair Trading Press Release|last=|first=|date=21 December 2006|website=National Ara chive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 Feb 2020}}</ref> The Bursar at the time was Carl Bilson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/_2v6dAdpo4YcFzO_a8bWST3hKgA/appointments|title=Carl Peter BILSON - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House)|website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\nFemale staff members were paid 56-57% less than their male coworkers at the school in 2018,<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://gender-pay-gap.service.gov.uk/Employer/2xIbxNxU/2018|title=Repton School gender pay gap data / 2018-19 - GOV.UK|website=gender-pay-gap.service.gov.uk|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> and 50% less in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gender-pay-gap.service.gov.uk/Employer/2xIbxNxU/2019|title=REPTON SCHOOL gender pay gap data / 2019-20 - GOV.UK|website=gender-pay-gap.service.gov.uk|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n== International schools ==\n[[File:WTemple.jpg|thumb|William Temple was headmaster of Repton, but went on to become Arch Bishop of Canterbury]]\nThe school set up Repton International Schools Ltd (RISL) in 2013 to establish, develop and maintain the highest quality British international schools. The client schools are generally funded by partners, sometimes private equity firms, who are licensed to use the Repton School \"brand\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reptoninternational.com/History-Aims-and-Purpose|title=History, Aims & Purpose |website=|publisher= Repton International Schools Ltd|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> RISL covenants its profits to Repton School Trust in the UK, which helps fund capital projects and bursaries.\n\nClient schools comprise: [[Repton School Dubai]], which opened in September 2007 and is situated on a site in Nad al Sheba;{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} Repton School Abu Dhabi, which opened in 2013 on [[Al Reem Island]], [[Abu Dhabi]]; Foremarke Dubai opened in 2013 and is located in Dubiotech, Al Barsha South and the Repton New English School in [[Amman]], Jordan.\n\nFurther relationships are in development in, amongst other places, Oman, India and China.<ref>http://m.burtonmail.co.uk/Repton-School-open-satellite-school-India/story-29049140-detail/story.html{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Yet another overseas offshoot was set to open in Bulgaria in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.staffordshire-live.co.uk/news/local-news/repton-school-opening-bulgaria-1859297|title=Repton School set to open new centre in Bulgaria|last=Pridding|first=Beth|date=7 August 2018|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Headmasters==\n{{div col}}\n* Thomas Whitehead (1621\u20131639)<ref name=\"Bigsby\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=68oHAAAAQAAJ][[Robert Bigsby]] ''Historical and Topographical Description of Repton''<span> Woodfall and Kinder 1854</span></ref>\n* Philip Ward (1639\u20131642)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* William Ullock (1642\u20131667)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* Joseph Sedgwicke (1667\u20131672)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* Edward Letherland (1672\u20131681)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* John Doughty (1681\u20131705)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* Edward Abbot (1705\u20131714)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* Thomas Gawton (1714\u20131723)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* William Dudson (1723\u20131724)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* George Fletcher (1724\u20131741)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* William Asteley (1741\u20131767)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/>\n* William Prior (1767\u20131779)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/><ref name=\"mons\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reptonchurch.org.uk/Monument.htm|title=Monuments of St Wystan's Church, Repton|website=reptonchurch.org.uk|accessdate=13 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303212148/http://www.reptonchurch.org.uk/Monument.htm|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* William Bagshaw Stevens (1779\u20131800)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/><ref name=\"mons\"/>\n* [[William Boultbee Sleath]] (1800\u20131830)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/><ref name=\"mons\"/>\n* John Heyrick Macaulay (1830\u20131840)<ref name=\"Bigsby\"/><ref name=\"mons\"/>\n* Reverend Thomas Williamson Peile (1841\u20131854)\n* Steuart Adolphus Pears (1854\u20131874)\n* Henry Robert Huckin (1874\u20131882)\n* [[William Furneaux]] (1883\u20131900)\n* [[Hubert Burge]] (1900\u20131901)\n* [[Lionel Ford]] (1901\u20131910)|\n* [[William Temple (bishop)|William Temple]] (1910\u20131914)\n* [[Geoffrey Fisher]] (1914\u20131932)<ref name=\"boy\">Dahl, Roald, ''Boy'' {{ISBN|0-435-12300-9}} (hardcover, 1986) (see also ''[[Boy: Tales of Childhood]]'')</ref>\n* [[John Christie (headmaster)|John Christie]] (1932\u20131937)\n* [[Michael Clarke (priest)|H.G. Michael Clarke]] (1937\u20131943)\n* Theodore Lynam Thomas (1944\u20131961)\n* [[John Thorn (headmaster)|John Thorn]] (1961\u20131968)\n* John Gammell (1968\u20131978)\n* [[David Jewell]] (1979\u20131987)\n* Graham E. Jones (1987\u20132003)\n* Robert Holroyd (2003\u20132014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/Repton-School-head-teacher-Robert-Holroyd-step/story-25715824-detail/story.html |title=Repton School head teacher Robert Holroyd has to step down due to 'ill health'|work=Burton Mail|accessdate=13 October 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926144016/http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/Repton-School-head-teacher-Robert-Holroyd-step/story-25715824-detail/story.html|archive-date=26 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Sarah Tennant, (acting head, 2014\u20132016)\n* [[Alastair Land]] (2016\u20132019)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/repton-school-head-harrow-safeguarding-1503167|title=Top public school head leaves to take up new role|date=27 April 2018|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=27 April 2018|issn=0307-1235}}<br>- {{cite web|url=http://www.repton.org.uk/New-Headmaster-Announced|title=New Headmaster Announced|website= |publisher=Repton School|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n* Mark Semmence (from March 2019)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://attain.news/announcements/mr-mark-semmence-appointed-headmaster-at-repton-school|title=Mr Mark Semmence Appointed Headmaster at Repton School|work=Attain|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n[[File:Basil Rathbone in Tovarich trailer.jpg|thumb|[[Basil Rathbone]], an alumnus of the school ]]\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n{{Main|List of Old Reptonians}}\n{{See also|Category:People educated at Repton School}}\nAlumni of Repton School are known as ''[[List of Old Reptonians|Old Reptonians]].''\n\nThey include:\n\n* broadcaster [[Jeremy Clarkson]]; author [[Roald Dahl]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Repton School 'helped inspire Dahl' to write Charlie|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-derbyshire-14896806|accessdate=24 February 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=13 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423090629/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-derbyshire-14896806|archive-date=23 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>;\n* sportsman [[C. B. Fry]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historytoday.com/richard-cavendish/death-cb-fry|title=The Death of C.B. Fry - History Today|website=historytoday.com|access-date=11 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603181750/http://www.historytoday.com/richard-cavendish/death-cb-fry|archive-date=3 June 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>;\n* actor [[Basil Rathbone]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basilrathbone.net/biography/|title=Basil Rathbone, Master of Stage and Screen: Biography|website=basilrathbone.net|access-date=11 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108205420/http://www.basilrathbone.net/biography/|archive-date=8 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>;\n* and engineer [[Adrian Newey]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/racing/top-stories/Newey-giving-shape-to-Red-Bull-dreams/articleshow/10361996.cms |title=Newey giving shape to Red Bull dreams - Times of India |last=Batra |first=Ruhi |website=The Times of India |access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Culture and cultural references ==\n\n\n\nThe \"[[The Stig|Stig]]\" character in [[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]] is said to have been named after the school's pejorative slang term for new boys, a private reference with the producer [[Andy Wilman]], who attended Repton with Clarkson.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Parkinson|first=Justin|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-31907458|title=The Jeremy Clarkson story|date=25 March 2015|accessdate=14 June 2016|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>[[File:Southern 926 Repton (37136522726).jpg|alt=1930s steam locomotive named after the school|thumb|1930s steam locomotive named after the school]]There was a steam locomotive called \"Repton\" named after the school in 1934: Southern Rail, class V, Schools No 926). \n\nThe school's motto, {{lang|la|Porta Vacat Culpa}} (\"the gate is free from blame\"), is a quotation from [[Ovid]]'s {{lang|la|[[Fasti (poem)|Fasti]]}}.<ref>[http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/ovid/ovid.fasti2.shtml Ovid's ''Fasti'', book 2], line 204</ref> \"The gate\" ({{lang|la|Porta}}) refers to the school's arch and, by a [[synecdoche]] of {{lang|la|[[pars pro toto]]}}, the school itself, whilst also being a pun on the name of the school's founder, Sir [[John Port (died 1557)|John Port]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rich|first=E. E.|date=April 1961|title=Pro Pelle Cutem, The Hudson's Bay Company Motto\"]|url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/pageant/06/propellecutem.shtml|journal=Manitoba Pageant|volume=6|number=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repton.org.uk/mainlist.html?pgi=head.hist|title=StackPath|website=www.repton.org.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222025326/http://www.repton.org.uk/mainlist.html?pgi=head.hist|archivedate=22 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TtgWAQAAIAAJ|title=Derbyshire Archaeological Journal|date=23 February 1987|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThe school has twice, in the 1930s and 1980s respectively, represented the fictional Brookfield School in a [[Goodbye, Mr. Chips (1939 film)|1939 film]] and a 1984 BBC version of ''[[Goodbye, Mr. Chips]].''<ref>[http://www.sundaymercury.net/entertainment-news/film-news/film-reviews/2008/06/19/movies-made-in-the-midlands-66331-21105972/ ''Movies made in the Midlands'']. Retrieved March 2011<br />- ''[http://derbyshire.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/repton-derbyshire-5268/ Repton, Derbyshire]''. Retrieved March 2011</ref> Around 200 pupils were extras in the 1939 film.<ref>[http://www.youandyesterday.com/articles/1930s:_A_year_of_tragedy_and_war_worries \"1930s: A year of tragedy and war worries\"]. Retrieved March 2011</ref> Similarly, pupils appeared as extras in the 1984 BBC version.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n== Royal Visits ==\nThe school has had the following royal visits :\n\n*[[Elizabeth II|HM The Queen]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|HRH Prince Phillip]] made an official visit to the school on 28 March 1957, to mark the 400 year anniversary of the school's establishment. The welcome was led by former headmaster Geoffrey Fisher and the Queen planted a [[mulberry tree]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishpathe.com/video/VLVA9V91Z64TJ4ODWHA29J4KQ6HUW-RTV/query/UK|title=Uk: Royal Visit To Repton, Derbyshire|last=Path\u00e9|first=British|website=www.britishpathe.com|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=UK: ROYAL VISIT TO REPTON, DERBYSHIRE ~ Clip #110164997|url=https://www.pond5.com/stock-footage/item/110164997-uk-royal-visit-repton-derbyshire|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n*[[Duchess of Kent|HRH The Duchess of Kent]] visited the school in June 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/news/history/duchess-kent-impressed-crowds-during-147021|title=A Royal visit for Repton in 1985|last=Sinfield|first=Stephen|date=2017-05-19|website=burtonmail|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* The school received a visit from [[Duke of Kent|HRH The Duke of Kent]] in September 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/archive/201309|title=September 2013|website=The Royal Family|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* The school marked its 450th anniversary in 2007 with a royal visit from [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|HRH Prince Edward]].\n\n== Social action ==\n[[File:Swimming 4x100m freestyle relay 2017-08-07 09.jpg|thumb|Adam Peaty attended Repton School after his talent was identified  ]]\nIn May 2016, the school made [[defibrillator]]s on its site available to the local community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/Repton-villagers-access-defibrillators/story-29261534-detail/story.html|title=Repton villagers give access to two defibrillators|date=12 May 2016|website=Burton Mail|accessdate=27 May 2016}} {{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Some of the staff at the school have been vocal about the issue of [[Traffic ticket|speeding]] traffic in the village of [[Repton]] and have participated in public [[Radar gun|speed gun]] enforcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Campaigners-Repton-Milton-gunning-speeders/story-11580107-detail/story.html|title=Campaigners from Repton and Milton gunning for speeders|date=10 July 2008|website=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=28 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008030618/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/campaigners-repton-milton-gunning-speeders/story-11580107-detail/story.html|archivedate=8 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe school's facilities are used by the wider community from time to time. The Olympic gold medal and world record holder [[Adam Peaty]] used Repton's swimming pool as a training facility. His coach, Melanie Marshall, teaches swimming at the school.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/aug/08/adam-peaty-swimming-club-celebrates-success |title='He's our hero': Adam Peaty's swimming club celebrates his success |first1=Josh |last1=Halliday |first2=Haroon |last2=Siddique |date=8 August 2016 |accessdate=13 October 2017 |newspaper=The Guardian |location= London}}</ref>\n\n== The old priory  ==\nRepton Priory was a 12th-century [[Augustinian]] foundation. It was dissolved in 1538. After dissolution, the Thacker family lived at the priory until 1553.  One of this family, Gilbert Thacker, destroyed the church, almost entirely in a day; he did this during the time of Queen [[Mary I of England|Mary]], fearing the priory would be recommissioned as part of the [[Counter-Reformation]]. <ref name=\"Page\">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=40125 \"Houses of Austin canons: The priory of Repton, with the cell of Calke\"], ''A History of the County of Derby'', volume 2 (1907), pp. 58\u201363. Retrieved 8 June 2013</ref><ref name=\"Rep\"> {{cite web |url=http://www.reptonchurch.org.uk/index.htm |title=Repton Church: Our Church \u2013 Christianity in Repton |accessdate=9 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618152029/http://www.reptonchurch.org.uk/index.htm |archivedate=18 June 2013  }}</ref>[[File:Arch and Old Priory, Repton - geograph.org.uk - 273607.jpg|right|thumb|The School Arch, formerly part of [[Repton Priory]], was moved to its current site in 1906.<ref name=\"PS\" />]]Only parts of the original buildings remained when the school was established. These comprised:<ref name=list>{{cite web|title=Remains of Priory Church|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-82775-remains-of-priory-church-and-the-chapter-|website=British Listed Buildings|accessdate=8 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=PS>{{PastScape|mnumber=1058695 |mname= PRIORY GATEWAY|accessdate=11 June 2013}}</ref>the footings of areas of the priory remain in some areas, uncovered during construction work in 1922; the bases of a cluster of columns of the former chancel and chapels; fragments of an arch belonging to the former [[pulpitum]], moved to their current position in 1906;<ref name=\"PS\" /> fragments of the door surrounds of both the [[chapter house]] and warming room.<ref name=\"list\" /><ref name=\"pastc\">{{PastScape|mname=Repton|mnumber=313097|accessdate=11 June 2013}}</ref> and largest surviving portion of the priory known as \"Prior Overton's Tower\", which is post 1437; largely altered, it has been incorporated into a 19th-century building.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1057669 |desc =Repton Hall with Prior Overton's Tower, Repton School|accessdate=11 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:NewHouseRepton.JPG|New House\nImage:ReptonThrotheArch.JPG|The Arch\nImage:Repton School, Repton - geograph.org.uk - 1650810.jpg|The Old Priory and Garth\nImage:Repton School - geograph.org.uk - 1303684.jpg|Pears School\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Repton School}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.repton.org.uk/}}\n* [http://www.foremarke.org.uk/ Repton Preparatory School website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141125142242/http://www.repton.org.uk/old-reptonian-society Old Reptonian Society]\n* [http://www.reptondubai.org/ Repton Dubai website]\n* [http://www.isbi.com/isbi-viewschool/1508-REPTON_SCHOOL.html ISBI Information on Repton School]\n\n\n{{Derbyshire Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Independent schools in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Repton School|*]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Schools cricket]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1550s]]\n[[Category:1557 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toDuchess of Kent(link changed toKatharine, Duchess of Kent) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repton_School"}
